The experiment's scan rate determines how quickly the applied voltage is scanned. Higher currents are seen as a result of faster SRs since they cause the diffusion layer’s size to shrink. The Randles–Sevcik equation (Eq. 3) explains how the peak current ip increases linearly with the square root of the scan rate (V s-1) for electrochemically reversible electron transfer processes involving freely diffusing redox species.3ip=0.446nFAConFγDoRT1/2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
